{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af1bdd0a-b914-4f43-9456-ff5fffc7e83d","content":"Use the `--filter` option:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nOr filter by class name specifically:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nThe `~` operator means \"contains\", so the first form matches any test whose fully qualified name includes `ReportExporterTests`. The second form does an exact match on the class name.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"954308bc-a383-46b8-ac96-6cdc6bef2fcf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to run only a specific test class using `dotnet test`. This is a straightforward question about the dotnet CLI - I can answer directly without needing to look at files.\n\nThe command to filter by class name in dotnet test is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nor\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nLet me just answer directly.","outputTokens":239,"requestId":"BC47:7FF88:2957CC:30372B:69FA94F6"},"id":"561a6dc1-6e1a-416d-bb04-6fddae92febc","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:10:20.173Z","parentId":"c295b51b-8f47-4dd7-be99-e885aac98fa3"}
